paragraph.docTitle:
Catalysis by allene oxide synthases (CYP74A and CYP74 
C
): Alterations by the Phe/Leu mutation at the SRS-1 region

subSection.paragraph:
The CYP74 family of cytochromes P450 includes four fatty acid hydroperoxide metabolizing enzymes: allene oxide synthase ( AOS ), hydroperoxide lyase ( HPL ), divinyl ether synthase, and epoxyalcohol synthase ( EAS ). All P450s have six substrate recognition sites (SRSs) in their structures. Some CYP74 mutations in SRSs leading to their interconversions including substitutions in “ F / L toggle” (SRS-1 region) were reported before. For further elucidation of the role of this site in CYP74 catalysis, the effect of Phe/Leu mutation on the specificity of selected AOSs was studied in the present work. Mutant forms of ZmAOS1 (CYP74A19,
Zea mays
), LeAOS3 (CYP74 C 3,
Lycopersicon esculentum
), and PpAOS2 (CYP74A8,
Physcomitrella patens
) acquired partial EAS activity. Mutant forms of ZmAOS1 and PpAOS2 possessed additional HPL activities. The results validate the significance of the “ F / L toggle” as a catalytic determinant of CYP74s, as well as the importance of the conserved Phe at this site for the AOS catalysis.

Cytochromes P450 are the haem-thiolate enzymes involved in numerous biosynthetic and xenobiotic pathways found in all organisms except obligate anaerobes (
Omura and Sato, 1964
; 
Nelson, 1999
). Majority of cytochromes P450 are monooxygenases (classical P450s). These enzymes oxidising the hydrophobic molecules use the dioxygen molecule as a second substrate and interact with the electron transfer chains (
Omura and Sato, 1964
; 
Nelson, 1999
; 
Werck-Reichhart and Feyereisen, 2000
; 
Ortiz de Montellano, 2005
; 
Denisov et al., 2005
). In contrast, the nonclassical P450s, converting the peroxides of hydrophobic compounds, are independent of dioxygen and electron carriers. These are, for instance, the prostacyclin (PGI 
2
) and thromboxane (TXA 
2
) synthases of mammals and other metazoans (
Brash, 2009
) and CYP74 clan proteins of plants, some non-mammals, algae and proteobacteria (
Nelson, 2006
). The CYP74 enzymes control the isomerisation or dehydration of fatty acid hydroperoxides to various bioactive oxylipins. Four 
types
of CYP74 clan enzymes are currently known, namely two dehydrases, allene oxide synthase (
AOS
) and divinyl ether synthase (
DES
), and two isomerases, hydroperoxide lyase (
HPL
, synonym: hemiacetal synthase (
Mukhtarova et al., 2018
)) and epoxyalcohol synthase (
EAS
).

The WT enzymes, as well as their mutant forms, were incubated with fatty acid hydroperoxides. The NaBH 4 -reduced (as well as the non-reduced) products (Me/ TMS ) of incubations were analysed by GC-MS. The structural formulae of the identified products of target WT AOSs and their mutant forms are presented at Fig. 2 . All studied WT AOSs specifically produced the α- ketols (allene oxide hydrolysis products), which were identified as Me/ TMS derivatives by GC-MS. Respectively, the NaBH 4 -reduced products of the WT AOSs were represented predominantly by the nearly equal pairs of threo and erythro vic -diols (see the NaBH 4 -reduced products of WT LeAOS3 and its F 108 L mutant form as the examples, Fig. 3 ). For instance, the 9(
S
)- HPOD conversion by LeAOS3 afforded the α- ketol (12 Z )-9-hydroxy-10-oxo-12-octadecenoic acid ( Grechkin et al., 2008 ), which upon the NaBH 4 reduction has been converted to the diastereomeric pair of 9,10-diols 1a and 1b ( Fig. 3A ), possessing the identical mass spectral patterns exhibiting M + at m/z 472 (0.11%), [ M – Me] + at m/z 457 (0.84%), [ M – MeO] + at m/z 441 (2.6%), [ M – C 11/ C 18] + at m/z 361 (12.19%), [ M – C 10/ C 18 + TMS ] + at m/z 332 (4.16%), [361 – TMSOH ] + at m/z 271 (66.31%), [ M – C 10/ C 18] + at m/z 259 (66.03%), [ M – C 1/ C 9] + at m/z 213 (40.40%), m/z 155 (64.93%), m/z 129 (32.80%), m/z 109 (25.36%) [ CH 2 = O + -SiMe 3 ] at m/z 103 (34.16%), TMS + m/z 73 (100%). Additional product of 9(
S
)- HPOD conversion by LeAOS3 was cyclopentenone, 10-oxo-11-phytoenoic acid (10-oxo-PEA), the NaBH 4 reduced derivative of which registered in GC-MS was compound 3 , the cyclopentanol 10-hydroxyphytonoic acid (Me/ TMS ). This product appeared as the diastereomeric pair of peaks with the retention time ca. 15.0 min ( Fig. 3A ). Additionally, the WT LeAOS3 produced a trace amount of 9-oxononanoic acid – 9- HPL product ( Toporkova et al., 2008 ).

The 13(
S
)- HPOD conversion by LeAOS3 afforded the only product – the α- ketol (9 Z )-12-oxo-13-hydroxy-9-octadecenoic acid ( Hamberg, 1987 ), which upon the NaBH 4 reduction was transformed to the diastereomeric pair ( threo and erythro ) of 12,13-diols 6a and 6b ( Fig. 3C ) having the identical mass spectral patterns: M + at m/z 472 (0.11%), [ M – Me] + at m/z 457 (0.48%), [ M – MeOH] + at m/z 441 (2.38%), [ M – TMSOH – H] + at m/z 381 (0.60%), [ M – C 13/ C 18] + at m/z 299 (32.06%), [ M – C 1/ C 11] + at m/z 275 (39.76%), [ M – C 12/ C 18 + TMS ] + at m/z 270 (15.33%), [275 – TMSOH ] + at m/z 185 (26.78%), [ M – 299] + at m/z 173 (60.63%), m/z 143 (4.35%), and [ TMS ] + at m/z 73 (100%).

Along with 9(
S
)- HPOD and 13(
S
)- HPOD , the WT ZmAOS1, PpAOS2, and LuAOS were also active towards the 9(
S
)- HPOT and 13(
S
)- HPOT as the substrates and converted them to the corresponding α− ketols, 9- hydroxy-10-oxo-12,15-octadecadienoic and 12-oxo-13-hydroxy-9,15- octadecadienoic acids, respectively ( Fig. 4 and Supplementary Fig. S1 ), the NaBH 4 reduction of which led to the formation of the diastereomeric pairs of 9,10-diols 2a -2b ( Fig. 4 ) and 12,13-diols 7a -7b (Supplementary Fig. S1 ), respectively.

Upon the incubation of LeAOS3 F 108L mutant form with 9(
S
)- HPOD , compound 4 was formed along with α- ketol and 10-oxo-PEA, as seen from the GC-MS analyses of NaBH 4 -reduced products (Me/ TMS ) presented in Fig. 3B (quantification data for the reaction products of all mutant forms are presented in Table 2 ). The mass spectrum of compound 4 exhibited M + at m/z 398 (0.15%); [ M – Me] + at m/z 383 (0.93%); [ M – C 1/ C 8] + at m/z 241 (2.29%); [ M – C 1/ C 9] + at m/z 212 (3.20%); [ M – C 1/ C 10] + at m/z 199 (71.65%). A prominent peak at m/ z 199 indicated the presence of an oxiranyl carbinol function with oxirane at C 9/ C 10 and a secondary alcohol moiety ( TMS ) at C 11. The mass spectrum corresponded to that of 9,10-epoxy-11-hydroxy-12-octadecenoic acid (Me/ TMS ) ( Toporkova et al., 2017a ). Catalytic hydrogenation of product 4 over PtO 2 followed by methylation and trimethylsilylation afforded product, mass spectrum of which indicated a structure of 9,10-epoxy-11-hydroxyoctadecanoic acid (Me/ TMS ). Thus, the mass spectral data substantiated the structure of 9,10-epoxy-11- hydroxy-12-octadecenoic acid for compound 4 .

Incubation of LeAOS3 F 108 L mutant form with 13(
S
)- HPOD resulted in appearance of major peaks 8a-8b , while as 12,13-diols ( AOS product) and products 10a-10c were minor products ( Fig. 3D ). The mass spectrum of compounds 8a and 8b were nearly identical and possessed M + at m/z 398 (0.10%); [ M – Me] + at m/z 383 (2.11%); [ M – n -pentyl] + at m/z 327 (0.83%); [ M – C 12/ C 18] + at m/z 285 (63.45%); [ TMS ] + at m/z 73 (100%). A prominent fragment [ M – C 12/ C 18] + at m/z 285 resulted from cleavage between oxirane and C 11 ( Toporkova et al., 2017a ), thus substantiating the structure of 11-hydroxy-12,13- epoxy-9-octadecenoic acid (Me/ TMS ) – epoxyalcohol oxiranyl carbinol ( EAS product). Catalytic hydrogenation of products 8a and 8b over PtO 2 followed by methylation and trimethylsilylation yielded saturated analogue, possessing the mass spectrum corresponded to the structure of 11-hydroxy-12,13-epoxyoctadecanoic acid (Me/ TMS ), thus confirming the identification of compounds 8a and 8b as EAS products.

The mass spectra of compounds 10a-10c ( Fig. 3D ) (Me/ TMS ) were also nearly identical and exhibited M + at m/z 398 (0.29%); [ M – Me] + at m/z 383 (0.96%); [ M – MeOH] + at m/z 367 (0.43%); [ M – C 1/ C 8] + at m/z 241 (33.02%); [ M – C 1/ C 12 + TMS ] + at m/z 173 (6.03%); [ CH 2 = O + – TMS ] at m/z 103 (17.01%); [ M – C 1/ C 12 – H] + at m/z 99 (57.67%); [ TMS ] + at m/z 73 (100%). A prominent peak at m/z 99 indicated the cleavage of oxirane at C 12/ C 13, as well as large peak m/z 241 corresponded to secondary alcohol ( TMS ) function at C 9. As a whole, the mass spectrum corresponded to that of (10 E )-9-hydroxy-12,13-epoxy-10-octadecenoic acid (Me/ТМS) ( Hamberg and Hamberg, 1996 ) – epoxyalcohol oxiranyl vinyl carbinol (also EAS product). Catalytic hydrogenation converted products 10a-10c into a saturated analogue, the mass spectrum of which approved the structures of 9- hydroxy-12,13-epoxyoctadecanoic acid (Me/ TMS ) for the hydrogenated product, and 9-hydroxy-12,13-epoxy-10-octadecenoic acid (Me/ TMS ) for compounds 10a-10c . Thus, LeAOS3 F 108 L mutant form possessed mixed AOS / EAS activity, and EAS activity was the main when mutant form was incubating with 13(
S
)- HPOD . At the same time, HPL activity of LeAOS3 F 108 L was the same with that of WT enzyme. The mutant form possessed trace 9- HPL (in the same amount as the WT LeAOS3 did) and no 13- HPL activities.

